{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A request whose signature does not match its body is rejected with a 401 response; the body is not forwarded.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at a module handoff boundary (HTTP handler -> signature verifier -> queue publisher). A pure unit test of only HMAC comparison would miss the required \"not forwarded\" side effect check. No real OS/network/subprocess is required; in-process request/response plus a fake queue is sufficient. Higher levels are disqualified because behavior text does not require real HTTP transport or external infrastructure.","test_description":"Wire handler + real signature verification + fake queue in-process. Send request with tampered body/signature mismatch. Assert HTTP 401 and assert queue publish was never called.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"An event is written to the persistent queue before the HTTP 200 acknowledgment is returned to the sender.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior is explicit cross-module ordering (handler acknowledgment must happen after enqueue persistence step). This is the Integration handoff escalator case. No real network/subprocess is needed; can verify ordering with in-process server call and instrumented persistent queue adapter (local DB/filesystem acceptable). System is rejected because behavior text does not require real HTTP stack failures, only ordering.","test_description":"Run handler wired to real persistent queue module (or local test DB-backed queue). Inject a controllable enqueue operation and capture timestamps/order: enqueue commit completes before response status/body is finalized. Assert 200 only after enqueue success.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The handler returns the HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing of the event to finish.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is orchestration between handler, enqueue, and async downstream worker trigger. A unit test of one function would miss async handoff behavior. Real OS/network is not required; a blocking downstream stub in-process can expose accidental await/join bugs. System rejected because behavior text does not require real transport-level effects.","test_description":"Wire handler with downstream processor stub that intentionally blocks (e.g., unresolved promise for 5s). Send valid request and assert response is returned immediately after enqueue, before downstream promise resolves.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The response arrives within 3 seconds wall-clock time even when downstream processing of earlier events is slow and concurrent.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a real-time, concurrent, wall-clock SLA under load. In-process fakes or mocked timing can hide event-loop contention and scheduling effects. REAL-INFRA applies: real HTTP requests and real runtime concurrency are needed to catch true latency regressions.","test_description":"Start the service process, preload slow concurrent downstream work, then send real HTTP webhook requests while earlier work is still running. Measure end-to-end wall-clock latency and assert each response is <=3s.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"An event whose ID was already received is not written to the queue a second time.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is dedup state propagation across handler + persistence/queue boundary. Unit is too low because duplicate detection often depends on shared storage/unique constraints. No real network/subprocess required; local persistence wiring is enough. System rejected because behavior text is about idempotency logic, not OS/network behavior.","test_description":"Wire handler to dedup-capable persistent queue/store. Send same event ID twice. Assert first request enqueues once, second does not create another queue record (and returns expected idempotent response).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.83,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"When the queue reports it is full, the handler returns 503 with a Retry-After header.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure boundary is error mapping across modules (queue-full signal -> HTTP 503 + header). A unit test of formatting alone is too narrow; must verify handler+queue interaction. Real infra is not required for this behavior because queue-full can be produced by an in-process queue stub. Higher level rejected since behavior does not require proving real capacity enforcement (covered by behavior 7).","test_description":"Wire handler with queue adapter that returns a typed \"full\" error. Send valid request and assert HTTP 503 and `Retry-After` header is present and correctly formatted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.76,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"The persistent queue actually enforces its configured capacity limit and rejects events that would exceed it.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior targets queue component with real persistence semantics (not just mocked error paths). Requires wiring queue logic with its local storage backend/config to catch real overflow enforcement bugs. System is not required because no real external network/subprocess boundary is specified; local DB/filesystem fits Integration.","test_description":"Instantiate real persistent queue backend with small capacity (e.g., 2). Enqueue up to limit successfully, then enqueue one more and assert explicit capacity rejection and no extra persisted record.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.84,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
